{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474389","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474389"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:20:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:20:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12051"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12051"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.67,0.04,0.04,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4617"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106571"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4617"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12051"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89044"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1223"},{"type":"tags","id":"1353"},{"type":"tags","id":"1627"},{"type":"tags","id":"1745"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6990"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7294"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39202"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42702"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43290"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44113"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106571"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 17-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-year history of irregular menstrual cycles. She reports fatigue and excess facial and body hair growth. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with pulse rate 74/min, blood pressure 121/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her BMI is 33 kg/m\u00b2. She has facial acne, hirsutism, and acanthosis nigricans in her axillae and neck folds.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following laboratory findings would be most consistent with the clinical presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["High FSH level","LH:FSH ratio of 3:1","High prolactin level","Low level of free testosterone","Low dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate level"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS), including menstrual irregularity, obesity, hirsutism, acne, and acanthosis nigricans. The diagnosis of PCOS is based on the Rotterdam criteria, which require two of the following three features: (1) oligo/anovulation, (2) clinical and/or biochemical signs of hyperandrogenism, and (3) polycystic ovarian morphology on ultrasound. When investigating irregular menstrual cycles, multiple hormonal tests are typically performed including LH, FSH, testosterone, free androgen index (FAI), prolactin, thyroid function tests, and sometimes DHEAS. Understanding the interpretation of these tests is crucial for diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELH:FSH ratio of 3:1\u003C/strong\u003E is most consistent with the clinical presentation. This elevated ratio results from abnormal gonadotropin-releasing hormone pulsatility leading to preferential LH secretion over FSH. In healthy women, this ratio typically remains between 1:1 and 2:1. The elevated LH drives increased androgen production by the ovarian theca cells, contributing to the hyperandrogenic state seen in PCOS. While an elevated LH:FSH ratio supports the diagnosis, it is not part of the formal diagnostic criteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh FSH level\u003C/strong\u003E would not be expected given these symptoms. FSH levels are typically normal or low due to negative feedback from elevated oestrogen and inhibin. High FSH is more commonly associated with primary ovarian insufficiency or menopause, which would present differently with hot flushes and amenorrhoea rather than signs of androgen excess.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh prolactin level\u003C/strong\u003E would suggest alternative diagnoses such as hyperprolactinaemia from a pituitary adenoma. Prolactin is typically normal in patients with these clinical features. Hyperprolactinaemia typically presents with galactorrhoea, amenorrhoea, and infertility, but without the marked hyperandrogenic features seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow level of free testosterone\u003C/strong\u003E would be inconsistent with the clinical features, particularly the hirsutism and acne which suggest hyperandrogenism. In PCOS, free testosterone is typically elevated due to increased production and decreased sex hormone binding globulin (SHBG) levels, the latter being particularly associated with insulin resistance. Elevated total testosterone and FAI are key biochemical markers used to confirm hyperandrogenism in the Rotterdam criteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate level\u003C/strong\u003E would not fit with the clinical picture. DHEAS is typically normal or elevated in patients with hyperandrogenic symptoms. Low DHEAS might suggest adrenal insufficiency, which would present with fatigue, hypotension, and electrolyte disturbances rather than the features of androgen excess seen here.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["In polycystic ovary syndrome, LH:FSH ratio is typically elevated above 2:1 due to abnormal gonadotropin-releasing hormone pulsatility","The diagnosis of PCOS requires two of three Rotterdam criteria: clinical/biochemical hyperandrogenism, oligo/anovulation, and polycystic ovarian morphology","Investigation of irregular menstrual cycles includes multiple hormonal tests including testosterone, FAI, LH, FSH, prolactin, and thyroid function"],"references":["Saadia Z. Follicle Stimulating Hormone (LH: FSH) Ratio in Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS) - Obese vs. Non-Obese Women. Med Arch. 2020 Aug;74(4):289-293.","Pe\u00f1a, A.S., Witchel, S.F., Hoeger, K.M. et al. Adolescent polycystic ovary syndrome according to the international evidence-based guideline. BMC Med 18, 72 (2020). https://doi.org/10.1186/s12916-020-01516-x"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89044"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12051"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89044","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89044"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-20T19:13:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-20T19:17:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4617"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106571"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedA